  "model": "deepseek-v4-flash",
  "response_text": "This is a fantastic and important goal. A healthy eating plan for a single parent needs to be **realistic, flexible, and low-stress**. Forget complicated recipes and hours of meal prep. The key is to work smarter, not harder.\n\nHere is a practical, healthy eating plan designed for a single parent managing work and childcare.\n\n### Core Philosophy: The 3 Pillars\n\n1.  **Strategic Simplicity:** Fewer ingredients, fewer steps, fewer dishes.\n2.  **Planned Leftovers:** Cook once, eat twice (or three times).\n3.  **The \"Deconstructed\" Method:** Cook components, not complete meals, so everyone can assemble their own plate (reducing food battles).\n\n---\n\n### The Strategy: A 3-Step Weekly Plan\n\n**Step 1: The Sunday \"Power Hour\" (1 hour max)**\n\nThis is your secret weapon. Don't call it \"meal prep\" – it's just a quick session to set yourself up for success.\n\n- **Wash & Chop:** Wash and chop 1-2 bell peppers, 1 onion, and a bag of carrots. Store in airtight containers.\n- **Cook a Grain:** Make a big batch of brown rice, quinoa, or whole-wheat pasta.\n- **Cook a Protein:** Bake a tray of chicken thighs (bone-in, skin-on for flavor and ease), hard-boil 6-8 eggs, or cook a pound of ground turkey/beef.\n- **Wash Greens:** Wash and dry a large container of mixed greens or spinach. They'll last all week.\n- **Portion Snacks:** Put baby carrots, apple slices, cheese sticks, and yogurt cups into grab-and-go bags/containers.\n\n**Step 2: Build Your Weekly \"Core 5\" Ingredients**\n\nThese are the building blocks for almost every meal. Keep them stocked.\n\n- **Protein:** Canned beans (black, chickpeas), eggs, rotisserie chicken (buy pre-cooked!), Greek yogurt, frozen shrimp.\n- **Grains:** Oats, whole-wheat bread, brown rice (pre-cooked from Sunday), whole-wheat tortillas.\n- **Veggies:** Frozen broccoli/spinach/mixed vegetables, bagged salad, baby carrots, bell peppers.\n- **Fruits:** Bananas, apples, frozen berries (for smoothies), oranges.\n- **Pantry Heroes:** Olive oil, salt, pepper, garlic powder, a jar of marinara sauce, salsa, peanut butter.\n\n**Step 3: The \"No-Recipe\" Meal Framework**\n\nForget exact recipes. Use this formula for 90% of your dinners.\n\n> **A Protein + A Veggie + A Carb + A Flavor Booster**\n\n- **Example 1:** Rotisserie chicken + Frozen broccoli + Pre-cooked brown rice + Soy sauce & sriracha.\n- **Example 2:** Canned black beans + Bagged salad + Crushed tortilla chips + Salsa & Greek yogurt (as sour cream).\n- **Example 3:** Scrambled eggs + Frozen spinach + Whole-wheat toast + Avocado slices.\n\n---\n\n### A Sample Week of Low-Stress Meals\n\n**Monday (Busy Day):**\n- **Breakfast:** Overnight oats (mix oats, milk, yogurt, berries in a jar the night before).\n- **Lunch:** Leftover \"Deconstructed Burrito Bowl\" from Sunday (rice, beans, chicken, cheese, salsa).\n- **Dinner:** **Sheet Pan Salmon & Veggies.** Salmon fillets + frozen broccoli + olive oil + salt/pepper. Bake at 400°F (200°C) for 15-20 min. Done.\n\n**Tuesday (Leftover Magic):**\n- **Breakfast:** Greek yogurt with berries and a handful of granola.\n- **Lunch:** Hard-boiled egg salad sandwich on whole-wheat bread.\n- **Dinner:** **\"Kitchen Sink\" Pasta.** Cook pasta. Toss with jarred marinara, leftover rotisserie chicken, and a handful of frozen spinach. Serve with a bagged salad.\n\n**Wednesday (Slow Cooker/Crockpot Day):**\n- **Breakfast:** Banana and a cheese stick.\n- **Lunch:** Leftover pasta from Tuesday.\n- **Dinner:** **Throw-It-In Chicken & Veggie Stew.** Throw chicken breasts (or thighs), a bag of frozen mixed veggies, a can of diced tomatoes, and some broth into the slow cooker in the morning. Come home to a ready meal.\n\n**Thursday (Fun & Fast):**\n- **Breakfast:** Smoothie (frozen berries, banana, spinach, milk/yogurt).\n- **Lunch:** Leftover stew from Wednesday.\n- **Dinner:** **DIY \"Lunchable\" Plate.** Whole-wheat crackers, cheese slices, turkey slices, apple slices, baby carrots. Fun for kids, no cooking for you.\n\n**Friday (Treat Yourself & Let Go):**\n- **Breakfast:** Scrambled eggs (use Sunday's pre-chopped veggies).\n- **Lunch:** Leftover \"Lunchable\" plate or a simple salad with leftover protein.\n- **Dinner:** **Order In.** Seriously. You've earned it. Choose a slightly healthier option (e.g., veggie-packed pizza, a stir-fry, or a grilled chicken wrap). No guilt.\n\n**Weekend (Relaxed):**\n- **Breakfast:** Pancakes (use whole-wheat mix) with fruit. Make extra for the freezer.\n- **Lunch:** \"Clean-out-the-fridge\" omelets or frittatas.\n- **Dinner:** **Build-Your-Own Tacos.** Ground beef/turkey, beans, shredded lettuce, cheese, salsa, sour cream. Everyone builds their own.\n\n---\n\n### Survival Tips for the Single Parent\n\n- **The \"No-Cook\" Emergency Kit:** Always have canned tuna, whole-wheat crackers, nuts, and fruit on hand for nights when you just can't.\n- **The 20-Minute Rule:** Give yourself permission to stop cooking after 20 minutes. If it's not done, it's not the right meal for tonight.\n- **Double the Recipe:** Whenever you cook, make double. Freeze half for a future \"zero-effort\" dinner.\n- **Get the Kids Involved (Age-Appropriately):** A 4-year-old can wash lettuce. An 8-year-old can set the table. A 12-year-old can learn to scramble eggs. This builds life skills and gives you a few minutes of help.\n- **Hydrate Strategically:** Keep a large water bottle at your desk and in the car. Dehydration masquerades as hunger and fatigue.\n- **Forgive Yourself:** You will have a pizza-and-cereal-for-dinner night. It's okay. The goal is progress, not perfection. One \"bad\" meal doesn't ruin your health, just like one \"good\" meal doesn't make you healthy.\n\n**The most important rule: Your health is a form of self-care. Fueling your body well gives you the energy and patience to be the amazing parent you are. You've got this.**",
